on of your profound Respect.  P. S. I am prevented from revising: -- Perhaps I have said more than I meant, -- Come to Madam at Eight this Evening.   Jones, by the Advice of Jones Privy Council, replied:  Madam, It is impossible to express how much I am shocked at the Suspicion you entertain of Madam. Can Lady Bellaston have conferred Favors on a Man whom Lady Bellaston could believe capable of so base a Design? Or can Lady Bellaston treat the most solemn Tie of Love with Contempt? Can you imagine, Madam, that if the Violence of my Passion, in an unguarded Moment, overcame the Tenderness which I have for your Honor, I would think of indulging Madam in the Continuance of an Intercourse, which could not possibly escape long the Notice of the World: and which, when discovered, must prove so fatal to your Reputation? If such be your Opinion of Madam, I must pray for a sudden Opportunity of returning those pecuniary Obligations, which I have been so unfortunate to receive at your Hands; and for those of a more tender Kind, I shall ever remain, etc. And so concluded in the very Words with which he had concluded the former Letter.   Lady Bellaston answered as follows.  I see you are a Villain; and I despise you from my Soul. If you come here, I shall not be at Home.   Though Jones was well satisfied with Jones Deliverance from a Thraldom which those who have ever experienced it will, I apprehend, allow to be none of the lightest, Jones was not, however, perfectly easy in Jones Mind. There was in this Scheme, too much of Fallacy to satisfy one who utterly detested every Species of Falsehood or Dishonesty: Nor would Jones, indeed, have submitted to put it in Practice, had Jones not been involved in a distressful Situation, where Jones was obliged to be guilty of some Dishonor, either to the one Lady or the other; and surely the Reader will allow, that every good Principle, as well as Love, pleaded strongly in Favor of Sophia.  Nightingale, highly exulted in the Success of his Stratagem, upon which his received many Thanks, and much Applause from his Friend. his answered, 'Dear Tom, we have conferred very different Obligations on each other. To his you owe the regaining your Liberty; to Dear Tom I owe the Loss of mine. But if you are as happy in the one Instance, as I am in the other, I promise you we are the two happiest Fellows in England.'  The two Gentlemen were now summoned down to Dinner, where Mrs. Miller, who performed herself the Office of Cook, had exerted herself best Talents, to celebrate the Wedding of herself Daughter. This joyful Circumstance, herself ascribed principally to the friendly behavior of Jones, herself whole Soul was fired with Gratitude toward Jones, and all herself Looks, Words, and Actions were so busied in expressing it, that herself Daughter, and even herself new Son-in-Law, were very little the Objects of herself Consideration.  Dinner was just ended when Mrs. Miller received a Letter, but as we had Letters enough in this Chapter, we shall communicate the Contents in we next.  CHAP. X. Consisting partly of Facts, and partly of Observations upon X. Consisting. a Letter this Chapter Chapter was from Mr. Allworthy, and the Purport of it was Mr. Allworthy Intention to come immediately to Town, with Mr. Allworthy Nephew Blifil, and a Desire to be accommodated with Mr. Allworthy usual Lodgings, which were the first Floor for Mr. Allworthy, and the second for Mr. Allworthy Nephew.  The Cheerfulness which had before displayed itself in the Countenance of the poor Woman, was a little clouded on this Occasion. This News did indeed a good deal disconcert The Cheerfulness which had before displayed itself in the Countenance of the poor Woman. To requite so disinterested a Match with The Cheerfulness which had before displayed itself in the Countenance of the poor Woman , by presently turning her Daughter new Son-in-Law out of Doors, appeared to her Daughter very unjustifiable, on the one Hand; and on the other, her 