r. Blifil's coming to Town, (for Pang clearly saw the Intention of Pang Journey:) And what greatly aggravated Pang Concern was, that Mrs. Honor, who had promised to enquire after his Sophia, and to make his Sophia Report to Pang early the next Evening, had disappointed Pang.  In the Situation that Pang and Pang Mistress were a^ this Time, there were scarce any Grounds for Pang to hope that Pang should hear any good News; yet Pang was as impatient to see Mrs. Honor, as if Pang had expected Mrs. Honor would bring Pang a Letter with an Assignation in a Letter from his Sophia, and bore the Disappointment a^ ill. Whether this Impatience arose from that natural Weakness of the Human Mind, which makes it desirous to know the worst, and renders Uncertainty the most intolerable of Pains; or whether Pang still flattered Pang with some secret Hopes, we will not determine. But that it might be the last, whoever ha^ loved cannot but know. For of all the Powers exercised by this Passion over our Minds, one of the mo^^ wonderful is that of supporting Hope in the midst o^ Despair. Difficulties, Improbabilities, nay Impossibilities are quite overlooked by it; so that to any Man extremely in Love, may be applied what Addison says of Caesar,  The Alps, and Pyrenaeans sink before Man! Yet it is equally true, that the same Passion will sometimes make Mountans of Mole-hills, and produce Despair in the midst of Hope; but these cold Fits last not ^ong in good Constitutions. Which Jones was ^ow in, our leave the Reader to guess, having no ex^act Information about the Reader; but this is certain, that Jones had spent two Hours in Expectation, when being unable any longer to conceal Jones Uneasiness, Jones retired to Jones Room; where Jones Anxiety had almost made Jones frantic, when a Letter a Letter was brought Jones from Mrs. Honor, with which we shall present the Reader verbatim and literatim.  SIR, I should sartenly haf kaled on you a cordin too mi Prommiss haddunt itt bin that hur Lashipp prevent me; for too be sur, Sir, you nose very well that evere Persun must luk furst at ome, and sarrenly such anuther offar mite not ave ever happened, so as I should ave itt bin justly to blam, had I not excepted of itt bin when itt bin Laship was so very kind as to offar to make me hur one Uman, without mi ever askin any such thing, to be sur itt bin is won of thee best Ladis in thee Wurld, and Pepil who safe to thee Kontrari must be very wiket Pepil in itt bin Hearts. To be sur if ever I ave sad any thing of that Kine it as itt bin thru Ignorens and I am hartili sorri for it. I nose your Onor to be a Genteelman of more Honor and Onesty, if I ever said any such thing to repete your Onor to hurt a pore Servant that as alwais ad thee gratest Respect in the World for Mrs. Honor. To be sur won should keep wons Tung within one's Teeth, for no Boddi nose what may hapen; and to be sur if an i Boddi ad told me Yesterday, that I should haf bin in so good a Plase to Day, I should not haf believed an i Boddi ad; for too be sur I never was a dremd of any such Thing, nor should I ever ha soft after any other Bodi's Plase; but as her Laship wass so kine of her one a cord too give her Laship wass so kine of her one a cord me without askin, to be sure Mrs. Etoff herself, nor no other Bodi, can blammee for exceptin such a Thing when it falls in mi Way. I beg Mrs. Honor not to menshon any thing of what I haf sad, for I wish ure Honor all thee gudLuk in thee Wurld; and I don't cuestion butt thatt u will haf Madam Sofia in the End; butt ass to miself ure Honor nose I kant be of any farther Sarvis to u in that Matar, nou bein under thee Cumand off anuther Parson, and not my one Mistress. I beg Mrs. Honor Mrs. Honor to say nothing of what past, and belive me to be,  Sir, Ure Onur's umble Sarvant To Cumand till Death, Honor Blackmore.   Various are the Conjectures which Jones entertained on this Step of Lady Bellaston; who in reality had little further Design than to secure within Jones own House the Repository of a Secret, which Jones chose should make no farther Progress than it had made already; but mostly Jones desired to keep it from the Ears of his Sophia; for though Lady Bellaston was almost the only one who would never have repeated it again, Lady Bellaston could not persuade Lady Bellaston of this; since as Lady Bellaston now hated poor his Sophia with most implacable Hatred, Lady Bellaston conceived a reciprocal Hatred to Lady Bellaston to be lodged in the tender Breast of our Heroine, where no such Passion had ever yet found an Entrance.  While Jones was terrifying Jones with the Apprehension of a thousand dreadful Machinations, and deep political Designs, which Jones imagined to be at the Bottom of the Promotion of Honor, Fortune, who hitherto seems to have been an utter Enemy to Enemy Match with his Sophia, tried a new Method to put a final End to a new Method, by throwing a Temptation in Jones Way, which in Jones present desperate Situation it seemed unlikely Jones should be able to resist.  CHAP. XI. Containing curious, but not unprecedented Matter. THERE was a Lady, one Mrs. Hunt, who had often seen Jones at the House where Jones lodged, being intimately acquainted with the Women there, and indeed a very great Friend to Mrs. Miller. Mrs. Miller Age was about thirty, for Mrs. Miller owned six and twenty; Mrs. Miller Face and Person very good, only inclining a little too much to be fat. Mrs. Miller had been married young by Mrs. Miller Relations to an old Turkey Merchant, who having got a great Fortune, had left off Trade. With him Mrs. Miller lived without Reproach, but not without Pain, in a State of great Self denial, for about twelve Years; and Mrs. Miller Virtue was rewarded by him dying, and leaving Mrs. Miller very rich. The first Year of Mrs. Miller Widowhood was just at an End, and Mrs. Miller had past it in a good deal of Retirement, seeing only a few particular Friends, and dividing Mrs. Miller Time between Mrs. Miller Devotions and Novels, of which Mrs. Miller was always extremely fond. Very good Health, a very warm Constitution, and a great deal of Religion made it absolutely necessary for Mrs. Miller to marry again; and Mrs. Miller resolved to please Mrs. Miller in Mrs. Miller second Husband, as Mrs. Miller had done Mrs. Miller Friends in the first. From Mrs. Miller the following Billet was brought to Jones.  Sir, From the first Day I saw you I doubt my Eyes have told you too plainly, that you were not indifferent to Sir; but neither my Tongue nor my Hand should ever have avowed it, had not the Ladies of the Family where you are lodged given me such a Character of you, and told me such Proofs of your Virtue and Goodness, as convince me you are not only the most agreeable, but the most worthy of Men. I have also the Satisfaction to hear from Men, that neither my Person, Understanding or Character are disagreeable to you. I have a Fortune sufficient to make us both happy, but which cannot make me so without you. In thus disposing of Sir I know I shall incur the Censure of the World, but if I did not love you more than I fear the World I should not be worthy of you. One only Difficulty stops me: I am informed you are engaged in a Commerce of Gallantry with a Woman of Fashon. If you think it worth while to sacrifice that to the Passion of Sir, I am you; if not forget my Weakness, and let this remain an eternal Secret between you and  Arabella Hunt.   At the reading of Jones Jones was put into a violent Flutter. Jones Fortune was then at a very low Ebb, the Source being stopped from which hitherto Jones had been supplied. Of all Jones had received from Lady Bellaston not above five Guineas remained, and that very Morning Jones had been dunned by a Tradesman for twice that Sum. Jones honorable Mistress was in the Hands of His honorable Mistress Father, and His honorable Mistress had scarce any Hopes ever to get His honorable Mistress out of them again. To be subsisted at His honorable Mistress Expense from His Fortune His honorable Mistress had independent of her Father, went much against the Delicacy both of His honorable Mistress Pride and His honorable Mistress Love. His Fortune would have been exceeding convenient to His honorable Mistress and His honorable Mistress could have no Objection to Lady Bellaston in any Respect On the contrary, His honorable Mistress liked Lady Bellaston as well as His honorable Mistress did any Woman except his Sophia. But to abandon his Sophia, and marry another, that was impossible; His honorable Mistress could no^ think of it upon any Account. Yet why should h^ not, since it was plain His honorable Mistress could not be His honorable Mistress? Would it not be kinder to His honorable Mistress, than to continue His honorable Mistress longer engaged in a hopeless Passion for His honorable Mistress? Ought His honorable Mistress not to do so in Friendship to His honorable Mistress? This Notion prevailed some Moments, and His honorable Mistress had almost determined to be false to His honorable Mistress from a high Point of Mrs. Honor; but that Refinement was not able to stand very long against the voice of Nature, which cried in His honorable Mistress Heart, that such Friendship was Treason to Love. At last His honorable Mistress called for Pen, Ink and Paper, and writ as follows to Mrs. Hunt.  His honorable Mistress, It would be but a poor Return to the Favor you have done me, to sacrifice any Gallantry to the Possession of you, and I would certainly do it, though I were not disengaged, as at present I am, from any Affair of that Kind. But I should not be the honest Man you think me, if I did not tell you, that my Affections are engaged to another, who is a Woman of Virtue, and one that I never can leave, though it is probable I shall never possess Affections. God forbid that in Return of your Kindness to me, I should do you such an Injury, as to give you my Hand, when I cannot give my Heart. No, I had much rather starve than be guilty of that. Even though His honorable Mistress His honorable Mistress were married to another, I would not marry you unless my Heart had entirely effaced all Impressions of His honorable Mistress. Be assured that your Secret was not more safe in your own Breast, than in that of,  Your most obliged, and 'Grateful Humble Servant, Tom Jones.   When our Hero had finished and sent this Letter, our Hero went to our Hero Scrutore, took out Miss Western's Muff, kissed this Letter several Times, and then strutted some Turns about our Hero Room with more Satisfaction of Mind than ever any Irishman felt in carrying off a Fortune of fifty Thousand Pounds.  CHAP. XII. A Discovery made by Partridge. WHILE Jones was exulting in the Consciousness of Jones Integrity, Partridge came capering into the Room, as was Partridge Custom when Partridge brought, or fancied Partridge brought, any good Tidings. Partridge had been dispatched that Morning, by Partridge Master, with Orders to endeavor, by the Servants of Lady Bellaston, or by any other Means, to discover whither his Sophia had been conveyed; and Partridge now returned, and with a joyful Countenance told our Hero, that Partridge had found the lost Bird. 'I have seen, Sir, says Sir, black George, the Game-keeper, who is one of the Servants whom the Squire has brought with the Squire to Town. I knew the Squire presently, though I have not seen the Squire these several Years; but you know, Sir, the Squire is a very remarkable Man, or to use a purer Phrase, the Squire has a most remarkable Beard, the largest and blackest I ever saw. It was some Time however before black George could recollect me.' -- 'Well, but what is your good News? cries Jones, what do you know of his Sophia?' -- 'You shall know presently, Sir, answered Partridge, I am coming to it as fast as I can. -- You are so impatient, Sir, you would come to the Infinitive Mood, before you can get to the Imperative. As I was saying, Sir, it was some Time before Sir recollected my Face.' -- 'Confound your Face, cries Jones, what of his Sophia?' -- 'Nay, Sir, answered Partridge, I know nothing more of his Sophia, than what I am going to tell you; and I should have told you all before this if you had not interrupted me; but if you look so angry at me, you will frighten all of out this of my Head, or to use a purer Phrase, out of my Memory. I never saw you look so angry since the Day we left Upton, which I shall remember if I was to live a thousand Years.' 'Well, pray go on in your own Way', said Jones, 'you are resolved to make me mad I find. 'Not for the World, answered Partridge, I have suffered enough for that already; which as I said, I shall bear in my Remembrance the longest Day I have to live,' -- 'Well but black George?' cries Jones. -- 'Well, Sir, as I was saying, it was a long Time before Sir could recollect me, for indeed I am very much altered since I saw Sir. Non sum qualis eram. I have had Troubles in the World, and nothing alters a Man so much as Grief. I have heard it will change the Color of a Man's Hair in a Night. However, at last, know me a Man did, that is sure enough; for we were both of an Age, and were at the same Charity School. George was a great Dunce, but no Matter for that; all Men do not thrive in the World the World according to all Men Learning. I am sure I have Reason to say so; but it will be all one a Thousand Years hence. Well, Sir, -- where was I? -- O -- well, we no sooner knew each other, than after many hearty Shakes by the Hand, we agreed to go to an Alehouse and take a Pot, and by good Luck the Beer was some of the best I have met with since I have been in Town. -- Now, Sir, I am coming to the Point; for no sooner did I name you, and told Sir, that you and I came to Town together, and had lived together ever since, than Sir called for another Pot, and swore Sir would drink to your Health; and indeed Sir drank your Health so heartily, that I was overjoyed to see there was so much